The only real reason to keep government involved in marriage is that there are complex legal repercussions of this union.  While marriage sometimes (certainly historically and currently not always) starts with love, and usually (but not always) involves a religious ceremony, in the end it is a grand civil contract.  It has implications in property, legal guardianship over and access to children, power of attorney, inheritance, shared government and job benefits and responsibilities...well I guess I really don't have to try and list em all, most people know this.<br>
<br>
You can never remove the State from marriage due to the legal nature of that contractual union.  The mechanisms of legally working out the consequences of changes to or breaches of that contract are entirely in the Judicial branch of government, and I certainly wouldn't want some church council working them out.<br>
