<br>
The government was just in the midst of a cross country set of hearing to get public feedback on three options:<br>
<br>
1) do nothing and leave marriage opposite sex only (found to be unconstitutional since then)<br>
<br>
2) create a domestic partnership regime (found to be unconstitutional since then)<br>
<br>
3) change the definition of marriage to include same sex couples (legislation being drafted to do just that being referred to our Supreme Court to determine its constitutionality as we speak)<br>
<br>
4) get out of the business of marriage altogether - this was the most novel route and one which was liked by neither the social conservatives or liberals - the conservatives wanted to maintain &quot;marriage&quot; as an important legal institution and the liberals insist that important legal institutions need to be equally available to all.  <br>
<br>
The gay and lesbian community had little desire to be seen as &quot;killing marriage for everyone&quot; so doing away with the state's involvement in marriage was not seen as a good outcome. <br>
<br>
On a side note, the concern that Adam and Steve will encourage little Johnny to be a homosexual is premised on it being preferential that Johnny become a heterosexual.  Given the equality guarantees under our constitution, based on recognizing the inherent self-worth of all individuals, encouraging heterosexuality is not a legally justifiable goal of the state.<br>
<br>
As America's Justice Scalia would say, &quot;&quot;the court has largely signed on to the so-called homosexual agenda&quot;.<br>
<br>
Just a little Canadian perspective on where we're at compared to the US.<br>
<br>
